<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAMMEUS-SPACE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEAVE YOUR REGRETS IN MILWAUKEE AND HEAD FOR SPACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL TAMMEUS  
 c. 1998 KANSAS CITY STAR 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I am not looking for your sympathy when I reveal that several
times in my life I have found myself in Milwaukee. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It is an occupational hazard for journalists. Keep at this
oddness long enough and eventually you find yourself in Milwaukee.
And sooner or later you will regret something about Milwaukee. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the best time I ever had in Milwaukee was in 1976 when I
was trailing around the late Sen. Eugene McCarthy, who was running
for president again with no hope of winning but with too many good
ideas to go to bed at night without having shared them with
somebody who could vote. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   We were in the kitchen of someone's Milwaukee house for a
fund-raiser, and McCarthy was regaling the crowd with spectacularly
funny baseball stories from back when he played in the Sioux League
or some such in Minnesota or wherever. As you can tell, details of
McCarthy's baseball stories have become far too sketchy for me to
recount here. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It turns out, by the way, that spending campaign time
entertaining people in Milwaukee kitchens with hilarious baseball
stories is no way to get to the White House. Remember that if you
long to be the most powerful human being in the world. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   My regret about Milwaukee, however, has nothing to do with 1976.
Rather, it has to do with 1998. That's because I failed to be in
Milwaukee recently for the International Space Development
conference at which former astronaut Edwin ``Buzz'' Aldrin spoke
about space tourism. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mark this down: Space tourism is an idea whose time will come,
and Buzz Aldrin's promotion of the idea will be seen one day as the
turning point. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Space tourism: Houston, we have an idea. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``That's my message to the astronauts,'' Aldrin said. ``If they
want to go to the moon or Mars, they better get behind (space)
tourism.'' It's the only way, he said, to create ``a great
consensus of people'' behind the nation's space program. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I am almost immediately attached emotionally to the idea of
vacationers taking off in rocket ships. For one thing, imagine the
cool message you could leave on your answering machine: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Hi. This is Bill. I can't come to the phone right now because
I'm traveling at 22,000 miles an hour on a spacecraft toward the
planet Tralfamador in the X220PU Galaxy. Leave a message at the
beep. Remember to tell me what year you called.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tell me you wouldn't love to be able to greet callers with that
message. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, of course, there will be limited space (what irony,
eh?) available at first for space tourists. At least until
Southwest Airlines, say, buys NASA and starts selling $79 tickets
to Pluto. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Aldrin's answer the the space problem is to create a lottery
system that would pick who gets to go. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Well, that might work, but if it were up to me I think I'd
decide on the basis of an essay contest. I don't mean that people
would write the essays saying why they want to go. Rather, I'd have
others write essays telling why they wanted to get rid of someone
by sending him or her into space. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In essence, we'd be searching for the country's most annoying
people and then unloading them into the cosmos. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   You may wonder why I was imagining my own answering machine
message if the idea is to find the most annoying people. Surely,
you're thinking, I don't count myself among the most annoying. No,
but if I continue to devote the first third of my columns on
something else to Milwaukee, you may. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Tammeus is a columnist for The Kansas City Star. This
article was distributed by The New York Times News Service. E-mail:
tammeus(at)kcstar.com.) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
