<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROSENFELD-SHORTTAKES02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SHORT TAKES: Author, author _ kill, kill
 &HT;    By Arnold Rosenfeld
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   I don't usually hand out bold advice I wouldn't take myself.
Still, I was glad to hear the Manhattan Theater Club of New York
City, which has a reputation for presenting new plays and talent,
has decided to go ahead with a touchy play after getting threats
said to come from Catholic extremists.
</P>
<P>
   The play was fated for controversy. Details are sketchy. The New
York Times hears the play is about 13 gay men celebrating the
passion of Christ and sex is involved. Furious protests arrived
punctually, threatening death to playwright, theater staff and
actors. The play was canceled, then reinstated a week later after
intellectuals squawked censorship.
</P>
<P>
   Catholics are hardly alone in objecting when values are
affronted. Name an ethnic or religious group, and you'll find an
insult that cannot be trivialized out of existence. Blacks, the
Irish, the churched and unchurched, Jews, women, Asians, Hispanics,
gays, you name it, have lines that cannot be crossed. And the lines
are movable, one person's insult being another's political
correctness. I would not find a jolly parody of Auschwitz a
liberating aesthetic experience.
</P>
<P>
   As a response, violence raises the stakes far too many notches.
Art is judged by its content and moral underpinnings. If playwright
Terrence McNally has gone too far, he will be found out, and
rejected in the marketplace. The only lesson to be learned as
things now stand is that someone has invented the ultimate
heckler's veto.
</P>
<P>
   Arnold Rosenfeld is editor-in-chief of the Cox Newspapers.
E-mail: arnold.rosenfeld(at)cox.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
