<HEADER>
A8123 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-BEANIE-INVESTMENT-R     06-01 0884
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-BEANIE-INVESTMENT-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIANA-ANA AND OTHER OBSESSIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For use by special arrangement
only. Asian and European points: Call Karl Horwitz in Paris for
details and prices, phone: 47 42 17 11; fax: 47-42-80-44). Latin
American points: Call Olivia Vasquez in Los Angeles, phone:
310-996-0075; fax: 310-996-0089). 
(jt) 
 By DOUGLAS MARTIN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Carol Hersh-Weiss collects, and then some. To enter her
sprawling New York City apartment is to venture into the nooks and
crannies of her decidedly idiosyncratic mind. Along one wall are 19
pairs of shoes, a small part of a collection of black shoes.
Elsewhere soda bottles bearing forgotten brand names like ``Cheer
Up,'' ``Dream'' and ``Just Whistle.'' Hidden in a drawer are
thousands of erasers, including one shaped like Ronald Reagan's
head.
</P>
<P>
   Antique quilts are everywhere, well over 100 the last time
anybody counted. They have multiplied in value 10 times over in the
last 15 years, with many worth more than $1,000. Mrs. Hersh-Weiss,
a professional potter, has told her husband, Norman, a
mathematician at Queens College, that quilts beat the stock market
hands down.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can make more money on my quilts than he can on Microsoft
and Intel,'' she said. ``He's not going to double his money and I
am.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Hersh-Weiss's optimism is shared by millions of other
Americans who are taking advantage of the strong economy to collect
stamps and coins as well as used beer cans in the hope that they
will increase in value. One in three Americans collect something.
Most of them don't care that collectibles, which is a term for
items made solely for the enjoyment of the collector, have
historically decreased in value than increased. They are more
concerned about the proliferation of fakes.
</P>
<P>
   Trade magazines estimate the collectibles market to be
approaching $10 billion in annual sales, and stories of resale are
legend. The Jetsons lunch box bought for $1 at a garage sale in
1980 fetching $200 today. The 1955 Murray fire truck that sold for
$50 in 1993 worth $250. The unused Hawaiian missionary stamp
selling for $575,000.
</P>
<P>
   Today, much of the collectibles action is on the Internet, where
millions participate in auctions held at hundreds of sites. It
helps to be in the news. Frank Sinatra memorabilia is suddenly hot.
All things connected with the millennium items will be collected.
</P>
<P>
   But white-hot publicity can be as fleeting as a sound bite: When
Princess Diana died, autographed pictures that had been worth
$1,500 immediately jumped to $50,000. The price has since drifted
back to about $3,500.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given the amount of material related to the events surrounding
Princess Diana's death and burial, it is safe to assume that supply
will exceed demand for centuries, not decades, to come,'' wrote
Harry L. Rinker in Antiques &AMP; Collecting Magazine. ``Even if 90
percent ends up in the landfill, supply will exceed demand.''
</P>
<P>
   Nowhere is the supply-and-demand equation more in evidence than
in the area of instant heirlooms. The Franklin Mint sells them by
the hundreds of thousands, including its non-firing replica of
Wyatt Earp's six-shooter and a 24-inch porcelain doll of Marilyn
Monroe in a feathered headdress. The company is in the business of
selling the glorious illusions that most resonate with the average
person. It bought Jacqueline Onassis's faux pearls for $211,500 at
auction and made replicas that became runaway best sellers at $195
each.
</P>
<P>
   But true value hinges on scarcity _ a bitter truth learned by
the 17th-century Dutch when speculators drove the price of tulips
to astronomic levels, only to see it crash with an abundant tulip
harvest.
</P>
<P>
   Today collectors seem motivated more by love, often tinged with
nostalgia, than by thoughts of making a killing. ``People end up
buying themselves a present in a way that means something,'' said
Alan Manevitz, a psychiatrist at New York Hospital-Cornell Medical
Center who has personally collected 25,000 comic books; baseballs
autographed by Babe Ruth, Joe Dimaggio, Mickey Mantle and Yogi
Berra, and Flash Gordon and Buck Rogers ray guns. Still, Manevitz
worries that people, including some of his patients, become  &UR; too &LR; 
obsessed. ``You shouldn't define yourself through your things,'' he
said, sounding almost convincing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just lose myself in it,'' said Hank Seiden, an avid
collector who runs an advertising agency in his spare time. From
the time he bought bought an F.D.R. autograph for $5 as a
teen-ager, he has always set a goal in his collecting. He now owns
the signatures of all United States presidents, and all members of
Yankees teams in 1927, 1941, 1951 and 1961. ``I'm not a nut,'' he
volunteered.
</P>
<P>
   Luck matters in collecting. On May 24, Yankee Stadium offered a
free Beanie Baby to every child. Produced in limited quantities,
other versions of the plush toys have gotten prices of nearly
$3,000, but the financial windfall, finally, seems to be ebbing.
Except perhaps for the free teddy bears given out by the Yanks:
Each of these carries a certificate with the date of the game when
David Wells pitched a perfect game. A cuddly, properly dated
specimen already resides in the Hall of Fame in Cooperstown.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
