<HEADER>
A8124 &Cx1f; tab-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JUST-IN-TIME-(FATHERS     06-01 0722
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JUST-IN-TIME-(FATHERS-DAY)-ADVISORY-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; EDITORS: In honor of Father's Day on June 21, The New York Times
Syndicate looks at the changing institution of fatherhood from many
perspectives. We examine the conflicts men face balancing work and
family, and the trend toward becoming fathers in middle age. We
offer two essays by dads anticipating Father's Day: one nostalgic
and one humorous. And for those dads who love to hit the links, Jim
McKay picks his ten top golfers.
</P>
<P>
   _ FATHERS, TOO, MUST BALANCE WORK AND FAMILY
</P>
<P>
   _ THE GRAYING OF FATHERHOOD
</P>
<P>
   _ THE MONSTERS OF FATHER'S DAY
</P>
<P>
   _ CONFESSIONS OF A GOLF ADDICT ON FATHER'S DAY
</P>
<P>
   _ TV'S DEAN OF SPORTS LISTS HIS TOP GOLFERS
 &UR; (HOW TO ORDER? SEE BELOW) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FATHERS, TOO, MUST BALANCE WORK AND FAMILY &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (1,600 words) &QL; 
 &UR; By JAMES A. LEVINE AND TODD L. PITTINKSY &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; From Child magazine &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Much is written about the struggles of working women balancing
work and family. But what about the working dad? In the 1990s, more
and more fathers want to play a significant role in rearing their
children, but the workplace is not always so accommodating. Levine
and Pittinsky describe how a father's work affects his family and
vice versa, and offer suggestions on how to achieve a better
balance. (slugged:
BC-WORKING-DADS-AND-PARENTING-(FATHERS-DAY)-NYTSF, priority code r,
category code l)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE GRAYING OF FATHERHOOD &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (1,800 words) &QL; 
 &UR; By MARTIN CARNOY AND DAVID CARNOY &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; From ``Fathers of a Certain Age'' &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As many women have children later in life and divorced men
remarry and have second families, many men in theIR late 40s, 50s
and 60s are finding themselves the fathers of newborns. They may
get mistaken for grandfathers, but this new breed of fathers brings
a fresh new perspective to fatherhood, the authors say, often
valuing their children as much or even more than work. But older
fathers also face doubts about whether it's fair to raise a young
child at an advanced age. (slugged:
BC-MIDDLE-AGED-FATHERHOOD-(FATHERS-DAY)-NYTSF, priority code r,
category code l)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE MONSTERS OF FATHER'S DAY &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (900 words) &QL; 
 &UR; By TIM HERRERA &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   This Father's Day, Herrera's children have asked him to take
them to see ``Godzilla.'' The request evokes memories of his own
childhood, when he and his dad would go to the movies on Father's
Day, a rare time for them to be together, just the two of them.
``The time a child spends alone with his or her father is special.
Too often it's taken for granted by both parent and child,''
Herrera says. (slugged:
BC-FATHERS-DAY-AT-THE-MOVIES-(FATHERS-DAY)-NYTSF, priority code r,
category code l) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CONFESSIONS OF A GOLF ADDICT ON FATHER'S DAY &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (600 words) &QL; 
 &UR; By JOE APPLEGATE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Lying in bed before dawn on Father's Day, Applegate dreams of
sneaking out for a quick round of golf. He alternates between
musings about life as a golf pro and counting the blessings in his
own life. Good sense prevails: ``There are those Sundays when
abandoning your family to play golf is maybe just a little sick.
Father's Day is one, Mother's Day definitely another.'' (slugged:
BC-GOLF-ADDICT-(FATHERS-DAY)-NYTSF, priority code r, category code
l) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TV'S DEAN OF SPORTS LISTS HIS TOP GOLFERS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (1500 words) &QL; 
 &UR; By JIM McKAY &QL; 
 &UR; From ``The Real McKay: My Wide World of Sports,''
</P>
<P>
   Jim McKay, the voice of TV sports broadcasting, lists his choice
for the Top 10 golfers of the past 40 years. In an exclusive
excerpt from his new book, McKay describes and assesses the big
names, from Jack Nicklaus to Tiger Woods. Some surprises are here:
He places Lee Trevino above Tom Watson and far above Nick Faldo.
Must reading for the height of the golf season and Father's Day.
(slugged: BC-JIM-MCKAYS-TOP-TEN-GOLFERS-NYTSF, priority code r,
category code l)
</P>
