</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-RED </SLUG>
 WINGS SIDER-TEX 
WINGS SAY STARS `DESERVED TO WIN' (For use by NYTimes News Service
clients) 
By DAVID A. MARKIEWICZ 
C.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ The broad smile that ran across the face of Red Wings
defenseman Jamie Macoun was about the only one visible in the
Detroit dressing room after Friday night's game with the Dallas
Stars.
</P>
<P>
   Macoun's good feeling was understandable: in the second period
he scored what proved to be the winning goal.
</P>
<P>
   But most Red Wings players were far more subdued, calling
themselves fortunate to escape with a 5-3 victory after blowing a
seemingly untouchable 4-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were lucky tonight,'' said forward Martin Lapointe, who
shattered the Stars' comeback hopes with the fifth Detroit goal.
``We let them back in \Rthe game\S. It's a lesson: When you go up
four-nothing in the playoffs, you can't let up.''
</P>
<P>
   Lapointe said Detroit ``Sat back a little'' after scoring early
and often. ``A lot of the adrenaline goes down,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   On the plus side, ``We never panicked,'' Lapointe said.
</P>
<P>
   Veteran defenseman Larry Murphy also was hardly jubilant.
</P>
<P>
   ``They outshot us badly the whole game,'' Murphy said. The Stars
had 34 shots on goalie Chris Osgood, to the Red Wings' 20 on Ed
Belfour.
</P>
<P>
   Murphy's reaction to Lapointe's goal with about four minutes to
play? ``That was a huge sigh of relief,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Even Macoun's thrilling moment was somewhat blunted. Of his
goal, he said, ``I didn't realize it was going to be as important
as it was.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the first half of the game we got some lucky bounces and
ended up being up four to nothing,'' Macoun said. ``We probably
didn't deserve to be up four to nothing, and the second half of the
game ended up indicating where the game was going.''
</P>
<P>
   Macoun was impressed with the Stars' effort after falling so far
behind.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've been the best team in the league all year long and
tonight they showed why,'' he said. ``Tonight was a very important
game and they smelled blood. They realized, for whatever reason,
that we weren't clicking tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Red Wings players were at a loss to explain why they weren't on
their game.
</P>
<P>
   ``The effort was there but the passes were off a little bit and
we were doing plays that just didn't work out,'' Macoun said.
</P>
<P>
   Red Wings coach Scotty Bowman said that his team was off form,
but that he didn't feel they had let up on the Stars after getting
the big lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Overall, I didn't think we were as sharp as we have been,''
Bowman said. ``I don't think we tried to be careful, we just lost
our focus a little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Macoun: ``The players and the fans all want to have a nice
easy game. We were up four to nothing, but maybe we shouldn't have
been. Dallas probably deserved to win tonight, to be honest with
you. I'm sure they're thinking they should have won.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
