<HEADLINE>
FOR SOME PARISIANS, THE WORLD CUP IS MUCH ADO ABOUT NOTHING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MIKE GREENBERG  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ The opera-goers were quiet and serious in the subway.
They'd just exited a riveting production of Alban Berg's ``Lulu,''
a tragic tale of a hooker with a heart of brass, at the Opera
Bastille, and they weren't exactly humming the tunes.
</P>
<P>
   At Chatelet station, where the commuter line from the new
80,000-seat Stade de France feeds into the subway system, the train
was invaded by a horde of young people dressed in the red, white
and blue of Paris-Saint-Germain, the city's pro soccer team.
</P>
<P>
   The pensive silence of the opera-goers was shattered by a lusty
chant. Echoing from one car to the next, billowing in the tiled
vaults of the subway stations, it sounded a little like the
Tomahawk Chop.
</P>
<P>
   The Paris team had just beaten Lens, 2-1, to win its fifth
French Cup. The team's supporters were ecstatic. The opera crowd
was oblivious.
</P>
<P>
   Some Parisians care passionately for soccer; others, perhaps
most, don't. To judge from the posters for sale in stalls and shops
and subway entrances all over Paris, the city's main passion is
neither soccer nor opera, but American film star Leonardo DiCaprio.
``Chacun a son gout,'' (to each his own) as they say.
</P>
<P>
   When the World Cup of Soccer tournament begins June 10, even
soccer-loving Parisians might find it hard to summon enthusiasm:
Three days after the French Cup victory, when French national team
coach Aime Jacquet named his provisional squad for the World Cup,
not one Paris-Saint-Germain player made the cut.
</P>
<P>
   The road to the World Cup has not been altogether smooth.
Complaints that France was hogging too many tickets for its own
people rose to the status of an international incident in early
spring, when the European Commission and Socialist members of the
European Parliament threatened legal action against the
tournament's organizers.
</P>
<P>
   When 40,000 additional tickets were released for international
sale, the phone bank was flooded with millions of calls. Moreover,
no arrangements had been made to put the buyers of those new
tickets in their proper grandstand areas, somewhat rendering moot
the high steel fences that are supposed to segregate the supporters
of rival teams.
</P>
<P>
   Acting partly out of a concern about possible violence, the
British government has been actively discouraging Britons without
World Cup tickets from visiting France during the event. The French
tourism minister last month raised British hackles by sending the
opposite message: Come to France to soak up the World Cup
atmosphere even if you don't have tickets.
</P>
<P>
   There'll be atmosphere and room for everyone, apparently. French
tourism officials are projecting a 5 percent decline in tourism
during the World Cup, despite an expected 350,000 World Cup
visitors.
</P>
<P>
   As of early May, rooms were still fairly plentiful in Paris'
less swank hotels for all but the opening and closing days of the
tournament. The better hotels tend to be fully booked.
</P>
<P>
   Giant video screens are being set up in public places in all the
World Cup cities to provide televised match coverage for the
benefit of those who can't buy tickets. The screens might be
especially appreciated in Saint-Denis, just north of Paris, where
the gleaming metal roof of the new Stade de France jammed local
television reception.
</P>
<P>
   The city of Paris _ which has a reputation for being gruff to
visitors _ has launched several efforts to help World Cup visitors
feel comfortable and welcome. Months prior to the event, an
advertising campaign appeared urging service workers such as
hairdressers, taxi drivers and waiters to be nice to World Cup
visitors.
</P>
<P>
   International soccer matches are always subject to excessive
passion and hooliganism, and authorities throughout France are on
high alert against terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   World Cup spectators are subject to body searches for weapons
and other prohibited items, including alcohol, laser pen lights and
``documents, tracts, insignia, symbols or canvas banners of a
political, ideological, philosophical or advertising nature ...''
</P>
<P>
   The police also have discretion to order drinking establishments
to close early.
</P>
<P>
   The French are working with other nations' police officials to
identify and track known troublemakers among soccer fans. All 10
World Cup stadiums have been equipped with surveillance cameras.
</P>
</TEXT>
