<HEADLINE>
SIGHTLESS MAN TAKES A DIVE AT 10,000 FEET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LORENA FIGUEROA  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Robert Dittman knows no boundaries.
</P>
<P>
   Blind since birth, the Civil Air Patrol communications officer
stationed at Randolph Air Force Base had no problems leaping from a
plane flying at 10,000 feet Friday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   With an Air Force flight suit on, Dittman had a 35-second free
fall at 125 mph before jump master Rick Meyers of Skydive San
Antonio Inc. opened the main parachute.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want to prove to people there are no limits, whether
they are disabled or not,'' Dittman, 20, said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is very depressing when people become handicapped and just
sit around not doing anything,'' he said. ``I want to inspire
people to set a goal like I have done.''
</P>
<P>
   Dittman, a sophomore at the University of Texas at San Antonio
majoring in radio, television and film, decided to skydive just
three days before his jump.
</P>
<P>
   ``I became bored on Tuesday and I decided to do something
exciting, like skydiving,'' said Dittman, who hopes the Civil Air
Patrol will give him his wings for the accomplishment.
</P>
<P>
   The Civil Air Patrol is a volunteer organization that assists in
air search and rescue missions and air crashes.
</P>
<P>
   Friends who accompanied Dittman to the airfield say he is
adventurous.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is normal for Rob to do crazy things,'' said Victoria
Archur, who read the liability forms to him before his jump.
</P>
<P>
   ``Motivation is his favorite word,'' Archur said.
</P>
<P>
   Meyers guided and shared a square parachute with Dittman
throughout the jump.
</P>
<P>
   Dittman, who didn't tell his parents beforehand, said he wanted
to skydive again.
</P>
<P>
   ``It felt great; it was the coolest feeling,'' he said. ``I shut
my eyes for a second, but then again, I can't see.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
