<DOCNO> NYT19980601.0331 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-01 17:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8814 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INTIMATE-EXAMS-HEALTH     06-01 0834
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTIMATE-EXAMS-HEALTH-770(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEACHING MORE GENTLE DOCTORING, ONE STUDENT AT A TIME 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(js) 
 By ERIN ST. JOHN KELLY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Alice Saltzman sees her part-time job as a mission. By working
with medical students, she hopes to make one of the most
uncomfortable aspects of medicine a gentler, less intimidating
process _ for both patient and doctor.
</P>
<P>
   A New York social worker turned actress, Ms. Saltzman, 36, and
her colleagues around the country are playing an increasingly
important role in medical education. Called genital teaching
associates, or GTAs, they use their bodies as models to teach
breast, pelvic and genital-urinary examination techniques to
medical students, residents and even doctors.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was a social worker, I became very concerned about how
women were treated,'' Ms. Saltzman said. When she learned about the
associates through a colleague who was in the field, she became
curious. ``I wasn't sure I was going to be able to do it. But now,
I feel like I'm helping women all over the world. It's very
empowering.'' Some days, she said, ``I come home feeling like I've
done such a world of good.''
</P>
<P>
   Since being introduced in the 1970s, teaching associate programs
have expanded to nearly half the nation's medical schools, if not
more, said Gayle Gliva-McConvey, a pioneer in the programs and the
director of the professional skills center at Eastern Virginia
Medical School in Norfolk. Such programs are reaching more and more
students, in effect changing the way the intimate examinations are
conducted, one fledgling doctor at a time.
</P>
<P>
   Now, in the era of managed care, the associate's role has become
even more important, as health care companies closely guard their
doctors' hours, said Ms. Gliva-McConvey. But the greater service is
provided by helping to train more nurses, doctors and other
practitioners to handle one of the most stressful parts of patient
examinations _ and in fact to conduct genital examinations at all.
</P>
<P>
   Men and women are involved in associate programs, but the
emphasis has always been on women.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was pretty clear we were doing a pretty terrible job
teaching medical students how to do pelvic exams,'' said Dr. Robert
Kretzschmar, now in private practice in Iowa City, Iowa. Teaching
was done at clinics on indigent patients who had no choice by
``terrified medical students looking at female genitalia on a live
person for the first time,'' Kretzschmar recalled from the early
1960s when he was an assistant professor of obstetrics and
gynecology at the University of Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   A few years later, Kretzschmar sowed the seeds of the nation's
``standardized patient'' programs, using average people to pose as
patients for medical students. He started teaching medical
interviewing techniques to his students using the wives of fellow
staff physicians at the University of Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   By the late 1960s, he had made the leap to the genital teaching
associates, employing an aide from the urology department who had
agreed to be a model for pelvic exams. She requested to be draped
so she could remain anonymous. ``The person was being paid, and not
exploited,'' he said, unlike the disadvantaged women at the clinic.
``It was a great improvement,'' he added. But it still was not what
he wanted: ``I wanted to get rid of the drape. I wanted the patient
to interact with the students.''
</P>
<P>
   At professional meetings throughout the 1970s, he explained his
program and the idea took off, he said. One medical school hired
prostitutes for its program. Others placed ads in local newspapers.
Kretzschmar, though, set about finding bright women who were good
teachers and who wanted to contribute to medical education. He
offered $25 an hour. ``These people could do a better job of
teaching than I, because they were using their own anatomy,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The genital teaching associate programs evolved with the
standardized patient programs, which now exist in 83 of the
nation's 126 medical schools, according to Ms. Gliva-McConvey, up
from 69 programs in 1991-92. Exact figures are not available on the
number of genital teaching associate programs, but anecdotal
reports indicate a strong presence.
</P>
<P>
   At the University of Arkansas for Medical Sciences in Little
Rock, for example, both programs have grown significantly, said
Mary Cantrell, who was an actress and a standardized patient before
become director of the school's clinical skills center.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, the school had one standardized patient. Today, it has
more than 200, including 30 genital teaching associates. ``The
impact it has on students and the amount of doctor time it saves is
amazing,'' she said. ``These medical students can end up doing a
better exam than a practicing nurse or physician.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   (MORE) nn
</P>
<P>
   Even after years with the books and the lectures, many medical
students admit they are hardly prepared for their first genital
exam. When confronted with their first naked patient they have been
known to faint, cry, vomit, become hysterical and sweat. If they
don't overcome those reactions while working with an associate,
they could experience them with an actual patient.
</P>
<P>
   ``All a student's folkways, all their traditions are being
challenged,'' said Cathey Bienkowski, who has coordinated associate
programs in the New York City area since 1982. ``We are what we
have been brought up to be. We all have certain values about nudity
and touching. The whole class is set up to be safe for the
student.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Josie Hasle, a retired associate who set up the program at
the University of Medicine and Dentistry of New Jersey at Newark:
``It's such an invasive exam. And everyone who walks through the
door has baggage. We help them move it from the personal to the
clinical.'' Beginning at Louisiana State University, she since has
managed the programs at Tulane, campuses of the University of
Texas, the University of Alabama and the State University of New
York, among others. With the associates, she said, ``The student
gets a nonthreatening teaching environment.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Mark Swartz, director of the Morchand Center for Clinical
Competence at Mount Sinai School of Medicine, where students from
six New York medical schools practice clinical skills, said that
the reluctance of doctors to perform routine pelvic examinations
needs to be addressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you compare the average 25-year-old medical student to the
25-year-old in public relations,'' he said, ``they are very
immature. Medical students have had much more of a sheltered social
background than non-medical students. From college they've been so
directed toward their career that, in many cases, their social
development has been less, and with fewer interactions. They could
be very good at science but they haven't begun to pass
interpersonal skills 101.''
</P>
<P>
   That makes such programs even more necessary, said Dr. Lila
Wallis, a past president of the American Medical Women's
Association and founder of Cornell University's associate program.
``It is every woman's right to have a painless, competent,
sensitive and communicative exam,'' she said. ``A woman with an
unpleasant one in her past means that she won't go for check-ups
and jeopardizes her health.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Wallis, an internist, is particularly incensed with doctors
who do not perform them. ``A breast and pelvic is just as integral
to the exam of a woman as an exam of the mouth, throat, lungs,
heart, abdomen and extremities is. Everything is intertwined in the
body. To separate it out is diagnostically invalid.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the associate programs work in different ways,
depending on the school, the model that Ms. Saltzman follows is
among the most sophisticated.
</P>
<P>
   Male and female associates work with small groups of four or
five medical students, residents or practicing doctors enrolled in
continuing education programs.
</P>
<P>
   Women work in teams of two, first demonstrating an ideal
doctor-patient interaction, beginning with a knock at the
examination room door, through the initial handshake and on through
the actual examination. Next, the medical students themselves
follow the process, from the door through the examination.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Saltzman and her fellow associates are mostly part-time
workers. They are often people who are used to being looked at in
their other jobs _ as actors, dancers and models. They are
well-trained as associates, and apprenticed. In a way, they've
donated their live bodies to science, for an hourly fee. In New
York City, women typically receive $175 for a three-hour session,
and men usually make $150 for two hours. Some, like Ms. Saltzman,
work more than a dozen of the three-hour sessions each year.
</P>
<P>
   Male associates function more as live models as a urologist
guides the sessions, though the men do interact with the students
by answering questions and explaining what is comfortable and what
is not during the genital and rectal exams.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone can do it, said Robert Speller, an associate for 12
years. ``Nude, and nude and examined are very different,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For some associates, including Ms. Saltzman, the work brings in
more than money. Last month, she said, she taught a medical student
who had never had a pelvic exam herself, and by the end of the
session, the student was ready to make an appointment.
</P>
<P>
   Tracey Wang, 23, a second-year medical student, was impressed as
well. After a December session of pelvic and breast examinations at
Jacobi Medical Center in the Bronx, Ms. Wang said with a mixture of
relief and confidence, ``I thought it would be uncomfortable to be
instructed from that position, but now I don't see a better way of
doing it.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Paula Stillman of the Lehigh Valley Health System in
Pennsylvania agreed. ``When I went to medical school, we made the
same mistakes over and over again,'' said Dr. Stillman, who has
worked with associates since the 1970s. ``Even a lot of experienced
physicians may not have felt an ovary. When you watch someone doing
a pelvic you can't tell what they're feeling. The only way you can
really tell is if the person you're doing the exam on can tell
you.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
