<HEADLINE>
GLOBE CRITICS RATE FILMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
 ! poor, !! fair, !!! good, !!!! excellent  
 
 !! 1/2 ``Full Speed''  An occasionally engaging film about a group
of young people in a Paris suburb and what happens when one of
them, a talented writer, finds widespread success. The film's
biggest fault is failing to flesh out the writer's character so
that his transition into a heel is sharper and the effect on his
friends more poignant. (Unrated) (Renee Graham)
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; !!! ``Home Before Dark''  &LR; Modestly scaled but insightful and
affecting take on an 11-year-old girl forced into assuming adult
responsibilities when her depressed mother attempts suicide and is
institutionalized. Impressive central performance by Stephanie
Castellarin in a sterling debut film by Maureen Foley. (Unrated)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; ! 1/2 ``Hope Floats''  &LR; Hope flops as this film never gets off the
ground. It wastes the sweet appeal of Sandra Bullock in a skeletal
and predictable story about a woman retreating to her Texas
hometown in pain and confusion after being dumped by an unfaithful
husband. The movie mopes around more than she does. (PG-13)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ! ``I Got the Hook-Up''  &LR; This is ghetto comedy as its most
crude. Rapper Master P, who wrote and stars in this offensive mess,
fancies his film about two criminals and stolen cell phones is a
screwball comedy _ but only those foolish enough to pay to see this
will feel screwed. (R) (Renee Graham)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; (FU)!!! 1/2 ``The Last Days of Disco''  &LR; The third and (the
filmmaker swears) last in Whit Stillman's set of three nightlife
comedies about preppies who talk smart and live dumb while sorting
out their lives and struggling to stay on the right side of cool.
Stillman makes canny use of the waning of the disco era and the end
of the youth the characters are afraid of losing. Witty, literate,
great soundtrack. (R)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; !! 1/2 ``Lawn Dogs''  &LR; Not unimaginative, but this attempt to blend
social comment and children's fantasy never quite coheres. A
10-year-old girl flees her fenced-in Louisville suburb to enjoy an
innocent but liberating friendship with a gardener her parents and
their neighbors regard as white trash. (Unrated)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; !!! ``The North End''  &LR; An invigorating debut film from the brother
team of Frank and Joseph Ciota, filled with raw freshness, danger,
atmosphere and a total avoidance of goombah cliche. Fatalistic
locals led by Frank Vincent take a dim view of the changes coming
to their storied neighborhood and of the strains on its codes.
(Unrated)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Globe movie critic Jay Carr's entire archive of reviews may be
retrieved from Boston.com, the Globe's on-line service on the
Internet's World Wide Web; key words ``movie reviews.'')
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
