<P>
   JORDAN _ For the first time in recent memory, the Chicago Bulls
look extremely vulnerable entering Wednesday's Game I against Utah.
Michael Jordan says appearances AREN'T deceiving. Jordan says he
thinks the Bulls have enough to win their sixth title. But he also
says the team is running on empty. Are the Bulls Beat-a-bull?
Jordan says ``yes.'' (Bunn, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA: 8
p.m.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   MICHAEL _ When the Bulls were trying to decide draft direction
back in 1984, they were torn between a couple of players. Then they
saw Michael Jordan perform in a draft camp. Case closed. Kevin
Loughery, now with the Hawks, made the decision for the Bulls back
then. He relives the series of events that brought Jordan to the
Windy City. (Denberg, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA: 7 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   BASEBALL-DRAFT _ Former Braves player Jeff Burroughs anxiously
awaits today's baseball draft, because his son, Sean, who won two
Little League World Series titles, is projected as the No. 1 pick.
(Rosenberg, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA: 7 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   HUMMER-COLUMN -- From the Division II World Series: This was to
be the only possible matchup that could be certified a true
championship, No. 1-ranked Kennesaw State College against No. 2
Tampa, strength going against strength. This was to be one of those
inevitable stare-downs that are intense, no matter the division.
This time, the Owls blinked. (Hummer, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
(s) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   MCCOY-COLUMN _ This isn't the time for manager Jack McKeon to
pull a Mount St. Helen's. Blowing his top isn't going to right
what's wrong with the Cincinnati Reds. First of all, what you're
seeing is what you'll get. This is not a championship team. This is
not a .500 team. Nobody promised a rose garden. Too many weeds.
(McCoy, Dayton Daily News) MOVED
</P>
