</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PROTECTING-YOUR-VISION-LIFEBEAT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAFEGUARDING YOUR SIGHT: YOUR EYES AND HOW TO PROTECT THEM 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's LifeBeat
lifestyle package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to LifeBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing articles with color art.) 
 By JACQUELINE STENSON  
 c.1998 Family Circle  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mary Ann Rafferty didn't know she had eye problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wanted a new pair of frames,'' she recalls. ``But when
the doctor examined my eyes, I knew by the look on his face that
something was wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   A few more tests confirmed that Rafferty had glaucoma, a disease
in which too much fluid pressure builds up inside the eye and
damages the optic nerve. More than 3 million Americans have
glaucoma, and 80,000 are blind because of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``My whole world turned upside down,'' Rafferty says. ``At 41,
all I could think was that I was too young to go blind.''
</P>
<P>
   Luckily, her condition was caught early enough to save most of
her sight. Two surgeries have allowed Rafferty, now 49, to see well
enough to continue working for a pharmaceutical company in
Berkeley, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   The best way to prevent vision loss is to get routine eye exams.
These checkups should include a dilation, in which eye drops are
used to enlarge your pupils, allowing a doctor to see inside your
eyes to check for signs of disease. These screenings are especially
important as you get older.
</P>
<P>
   In general, you should see an ophthalmologist or optometrist
every two to three years until the age of 40. After that, a yearly
exam is advisable.
</P>
<P>
   Following are the top causes of vision trouble, and what you can
do about them.
 &UR; GLAUCOMA &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What it is: This eye disease is often called ``the silent thief
of the night,'' because irreversible vision loss can occur before
it's diagnosed.
</P>
<P>
   As the disease gets worse, peripheral vision narrows. Depending
on the type of glaucoma, you may notice eye pain, blurry vision or
headaches.
</P>
<P>
   Who is at risk: People 60 or older, as well as African-Americans
and those with diabetes, nearsightedness, high blood pressure or a
family history of glaucoma
</P>
<P>
   What you can do: Get routine eye exams. Vision loss from
glaucoma can usually be prevented through eye drops, pills and
conventional or laser surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Latest news: Preliminary studies suggest that regular aerobic
exercise, such as biking or brisk walking, may help reduce your
glaucoma risk.
 &UR; DIABETIC RETINOPATHY &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What it is: About half of the 16 million Americans who have
diabetes suffer from this disorder, and each year more than 24,000
of them go blind from it.
</P>
<P>
   Diabetic retinopathy occurs when high blood-sugar levels cause
tiny blood vessels to leak in the retina. There may be no initial
symptoms, but later there may be blurriness as the retina starts to
swell. Blood vessels can also bleed into the vitreous humor _ the
clear, jellylike substance that makes up the center of the eye _
and cause vision loss.
</P>
<P>
   Who is at risk: Diabetics and those at risk for diabetes,
including African-Americans, pregnant women, overweight people and
those with high blood pressure.
</P>
<P>
   What you can do: To prevent diabetes, stay slim and exercise. A
yearly eye dilation can also help detect diabetes at its earliest
and most treatable stage. If you already have diabetes, monitor
your blood sugar carefully. Eat right, exercise and take your
medicine _ most cases of blindness from diabetes can be prevented.
</P>
<P>
   Latest news: To slow vision loss, laser surgery is often used to
seal off leaking blood vessels. Advanced cases may be helped by a
vitrectomy, in which a blood-soaked vitreous humor is replaced with
a clear solution.
 &UR; MACULAR DEGENERATION &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What it is: A progressive eye disorder that affects the macula _
the center area of the retina _ causing central vision to become
blurry or distorted.
</P>
<P>
   There are two types of age-related macular degeneration: ``dry''
and ``wet.'' The dry form, which accounts for 90 percent of cases,
occurs when macular tissue thins as a result of aging. The wet
form, however, is more serious and can cause sudden vision loss. It
occurs when new blood vessels grow and leak fluids behind the
retina, creating blind spots.
</P>
<P>
   Who is at risk: Anyone over age 65, or who has a family history
of the disease. Scientists have recently identified a gene that may
account for as many as 16 percent of AMD cases. Other possible risk
factors include a high-fat diet and smoking.
</P>
<P>
   What you can do: While there is no cure for AMD, some patients
with the wet form benefit from laser surgery to seal off leaking
blood vessels.
</P>
<P>
   Latest news: Scientists are looking into whether antioxidant
supplements, such as vitamins C, E and bela-carotene, and minerals
such as zinc can slow down the disease. And researchers have
recently found that a substance called vascular endothelial growth
factor causes new blood vessels to grow in the retina. They hope to
find drugs to counter its effects.
 &UR; CATARACT &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What it is: A condition in which the eye's lens gradually loses
its clarity. This clouding prevents the lens from bringing light
into focus.
</P>
<P>
   Early on, there may be no noticeable symptoms. But as the
disease progresses, vision will get blurry or distorted. You may
also become more sensitive to light, and colors may look dull.
</P>
<P>
   Who is at risk: Everyone will get cataracts if they live long
enough. In fact, more than half of Americans ages 65 and older have
some form of the disorder. While it isn't clear what causes the
condition, one recent study found that smoking 20 or more
cigarettes a day triples your risk of early cataracts.
</P>
<P>
   What you can do: ``Surgery is the only proven way to treat
cataracts,'' says Dr. Richard E. Braunstein, assistant clinical
professor of ophthalmology at Columbia-Presbyterian Medical Center
in New York.
</P>
<P>
   It's also very effective: More than 90 percent of patients who
have the procedure, in which a cloudy lens is replaced by a clear
artificial one, improve their vision.
</P>
<P>
   Latest news: Research shows that vitamin C may have a protective
effect. In one study, women who took as much as 250 milligrams of
the supplement a day for 10 years or more experienced 77 percent
fewer cases of early cataracts.
</P>
<P>
   Estrogen-replacement therapy in postmenopausal women may also
delay the onset of cataracts.
 &UR; REFRACTIVE DISORDERS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What they are: Visual disorders that occur when the lens and
cornea do not bend light properly. For instance, nearsightedness,
also called myopia, makes it difficult to see distant objects.
Farsightedness, or hyperopia, makes it tough to see close objects.
Astigmatism occurs when the eye can't focus because its cornea is
misshapen.
</P>
<P>
   Who is at risk: Nearsightedness often hits in grade school, gets
worse during the teens, then stabilizes until age 40.
Farsightedness often strikes after 40.
</P>
<P>
   What you can do: Get glasses or contact lenses. Or consider
refractive surgery, in which the cornea is reshaped with a surgical
instrument, laser or both. The average cost is about $2,000 per
eye. In radial keratotomy, tiny incisions are made in the cornea to
correct nearsightedness. A similar technique is used in astigmatic
keratotomy to treat astigmatism.
</P>
<P>
   Latest news: Photo-refractive keratectomy surgery _ in which a
laser is used to correct nearsightedness, farsightedness or an
astigmatism _ has become more popular in the last two years.
Nearsightedness or astigmatism may also be helped by a newer
procedure, laser in-situ keratomileusis, done with a surgical
instrument and a laser.
</P>
<P>
   While 75 percent of patients will be able to see without
glasses, perfect vision is not guaranteed, says Dr. Ernest W.
Kornmehl, a refractive surgeon at the Massachusetts Eye and Ear
Infirmary in Boston. Depending on the procedure, some people may
become more sensitive to the light. In rare cases, vision loss
occurs.
</P>
<P>
   But most patients are pleased with the results.
</P>
<P>
   ``PRK changed my life,'' says former contact-lens wearer Barbara
Murphy of Mineola, N.Y. ``I forgot how great it is to wake up and
be able to see on my own.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Jacqueline Stenson is a New York-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to LifeBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing articles with color art.) &QL; 
