<HEADLINE>
HIGH COURT OPENS DOOR TO SUITS AGAINST FEC 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill.)  (mk) 
 By LINDA GREENHOUSE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Supreme Court Monday opened the door to
lawsuits against the Federal Election Commission by voters claiming
that the commission has not adequately enforced the disclosure
requirements imposed by federal law on certain political groups.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-3 decision, recognizing what the court referred to as
``voter standing,'' was surprising for a court that has often
appeared to go out of its way to shield federal agencies from
having to defend their administrative actions in court.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration had argued on behalf of the FEC that
lawsuits of this type expressed no more than ``generalized
grievances,'' shared by the populace at large, and were not
sufficiently particular or concrete to come within the jurisdiction
of the federal courts.
</P>
<P>
   The decision was, however, little more than a pyrrhic victory
for the plaintiffs in the case, six former politicians and
diplomats who oppose U.S. support for Israel and were trying to
force the FEC to require a leading pro-Israel lobbying group to
disclose membership and financial information.
</P>
<P>
   While ruling that the six men were entitled to bring their
lawsuit, the court sent the merits of the nine-year-old dispute
back to the election commission under circumstances that make it
highly likely that the organization, the American Israel Public
Affairs Committee, will never have to make the disclosures the
plaintiffs have been seeking.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Stephen Breyer wrote the majority opinion, which was
joined by Chief Justice William Rehnquist and Justices John Paul
Stevens, Anthony Kennedy, David Souter and Ruth Bader Ginsburg.
Justice Antonin Scalia wrote a dissenting opinion that was joined
by Justices Sandra Day O'Connor and Clarence Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   The case presented the substantive question _ of interest to a
broad array of grass-roots lobbying organizations _ of the
definition of a ``political committee'' under the FEC Act of 1971.
Under the law, political committees must comply with extensive
record-keeping and disclosure rules, which include listing any
donor who gives the group more than $200 in a year as well as
disclosing the amount and purpose of expenditures.
</P>
<P>
   The law defines a political committee as ``any committee'' that
receives or spends more than $1,000 in a given year for the purpose
of ``influencing any election for federal office.'' The six
plaintiffs in this case sought in 1989 to have the FEC apply this
definition to the American Israel Public Affairs Committee, known
as AIPAC, and to require disclosure of its members and
expenditures.
</P>
<P>
   AIPAC, a nonprofit membership organization that does not endorse
candidates or make direct political contributions, argued that it
was not a political committee within the meaning of the law.
Because its spending was for communication to its own dues-paying
membership of 50,000 on political subjects of mutual interest,
AIPAC said, it did not meet the $1,000 threshold to be counted as a
political committee.
</P>
<P>
   The FEC did not agree, but it decided not to make AIPAC subject
to the disclosure requirements in any event. If an organization did
not have as its ``major purpose'' the nomination or election of
candidates, the commission said, it would not be considered a
political committee even if it came within the law's technical
definition. On appeal, the U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals for the
District of Columbia ruled last year that there was no basis in the
law for the ``major purpose'' test and that the commission would
have to treat AIPAC as a political committee.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In its Supreme Court appeal, FEC vs. Akins, No. 96-1590, the
commission argued vigorously that the six plaintiffs never had
standing to bring their suit in the first place. The government
argued that a policy dispute with the commission did not
sufficiently distinguish these plaintiffs from others with
generalized grievances or give them the concrete, personal stake in
the litigation required by Article III of the Constitution, which
limits the jurisdiction of the federal courts to ``cases or
controversies.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the plaintiffs was Paul Findley, a former Republican
member of Congress from Illinois who has blamed AIPAC for his
re-election defeat in 1982 and has publicly referred to the federal
government as ``Israeli-occupied territory.'' Another, James Akins,
is a former U.S. ambassador to Saudi Arabia. All are highly
critical of U.S. policy in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   In his opinion for the court Monday, Breyer offered a two-part
analysis for why the plaintiffs, and other voters in future cases,
were entitled to bring the election commission into court. First,
he said, the wording of the 1971 law, which authorizes ``any party
aggrieved by an order of the commission dismissing a complaint'' to
file suit in U.S. District Court, indicated that Congress intended
to permit suits of this kind, particularly when the suit requested
information of the kind that the law requires to be disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   And further, Breyer said, the lawsuit met constitutional
requirements by asserting a ``genuine injury in fact'' _ the
plaintiffs' inability to obtain information that, if they are
correct about the law, they have a right to obtain.
</P>
<P>
   ``The informational injury at issue here,'' Breyer said,
``directly related to voting, the most basic of political rights,
is sufficiently concrete and specific such that the fact that it is
widely shared does not deprive Congress of constitutional power to
authorize its vindication in the federal courts.''
</P>
<P>
   However, he continued, the court should not address the validity
of the disputed definition of a political committee because the
commission was currently considering a new rule that could make the
question irrelevant to AIPAC's status.
</P>
<P>
   The commission's proposal would take a broader view of the type
of ``membership organization'' that AIPAC has always claimed to be,
a change that would in turn be likely to treat AIPAC's expenditures
as ``membership communications'' rather than the kind of spending
that would bring it within the definition of a political committee.
In that eventuality, Breyer said, the campaign law would not apply
and the dispute over the commission's ``major purpose'' test would
be moot.
</P>
<P>
   AIPAC was not a party in the case before the court, but filed a
friend of the court brief suggesting the course the court took
Monday. A lawyer for the group, Thomas Hungar, said Monday that the
court ``did exactly what we asked'' and that AIPAC would ``clearly
qualify'' as a membership organization under the commission's
proposed new approach.
</P>
<P>
   In his dissenting opinion, Scalia said the court had expanded
the concept of standing ``beyond what the Constitution permits''
and that consequently the court should have interpreted the 1971
law more narrowly so as not to allow the lawsuit. ``A system in
which the citizenry at large could sue to compel executive
compliance with the law would be a system in which the courts,
rather than of the president, are given the primary responsibility
to `take care that the laws be faithfully executed,' '' Scalia
said.
</P>
<P>
   One of the plaintiffs, Andrew Killgore, said his group would
continue to press for AIPAC to be defined as a political committee
and expected to prevail in forcing disclosure of AIPAC's
activities. ``In the clear light of day, AIPAC's activities will
cease to be those of an 800-pound gorilla on Capitol Hill when it
comes to U.S. policies in the Middle East,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In a second case Monday, the court agreed to hear a government
appeal in one of the country's longest-running immigration cases,
the effort to deport a group of seven Palestinians and a Kenyan for
their activities in support of the Popular Front for the Liberation
of Palestine.
</P>
<P>
   The government has lost most of the numerous legal battles in
the 11-year-old case. Most recently, the 9th U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals, in San Francisco, ruled last July that a preliminary
injunction against deportation should be kept in effect to enable
the eight to collect further evidence to support their claim that
they are victims of selective prosecution based on constitutionally
protected advocacy of an unpopular political viewpoint.
</P>
<P>
   While the government regards the Popular Front as a terrorist
group, the eight have been involved in fund-raising and have not
been charged with any acts of violence.
</P>
<P>
   Federal immigration law has changed several times during the
course of the case. The government is now arguing that the most
recent change, the 1996 enactment of the Illegal Immigration Reform
and Immigrant Responsibility Act, retroactively stripped the
federal courts of jurisdiction over the case and should be applied
to lift the injunction. The government argues that the new law left
the courts with jurisdiction to review only a final order of
deportation, which has not yet been issued.
</P>
<P>
   In its order Monday granting review of the case, Reno vs.
American-Arab Anti-Discrimination Committee, No. 97-1252, the
justices narrowed the question to an intepretation of the
jurisdictional provisions of the new law. However, because the
lower courts have found that the Palestinians' First Amendment
rights are at stake, the justices may have to address the question
of whether Congress can close the courthouse door to constitutional
challenges to immigration decisions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
