<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DELTA-BRAZIL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Delta may buy stake in its Brazilian partner
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Delta Air Lines may buy a minority stake in Brazilian
partner Transbrasil, which needs fresh capital amid fare wars that
followed deregulation of the country's airline industry.
</P>
<P>
   A Transbrasil official told Blooomberg News the carrier is
negotiating to sell up to 20 percent of its voting shares.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd get fresh investment and technology, while Delta would
get a partner in Brazil,'' said Jorge Honorio, a Transbrasil
spokesman in Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta-based Delta, which earlier this year bought a 35 percent
stake in AeroPeru, declined comment on any negotiations. But a
spokesman acknowledged a continued relationship with Transbrasil is
important for Delta's year-old service to Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   ``The partnership with Transbrasil and the Brazil service have
been very successful,'' said spokesman Bill Berry.
</P>
<P>
   Under their current relationship, which doesn't include any
investment by Delta, the two carriers sell seats on each other's
flights. That means Delta can book passengers not just between
Atlanta and Sao Paulo and Rio de Janeiro, the two cities where its
jets fly, but also to Transbrasil's destinations within Brazil.
Transbrasil, likewise, can book passengers on Delta's U.S. flights.
Delta earlier had a similar deal with Varig, a larger Brazilian
carrier, but Varig called off the partnership last year.
</P>
<P>
   Marketing pacts with in-country carriers is a key to Delta's
Latin expansion plans, as well as those of other U.S. carriers.
Equity purchases by U.S. carriers reflect the value they put on the
deals. For instance, AeroPeru also needed capital and was able to
make itself the object of a bidding war between Delta and
Continental Airlines. Delta starts Peru service this summer. Delta
also has a partnership with Aeropostal of Venezuela, where it
started service in April, but that deal does not include any
investment.
</P>
<P>
   Delta has numerous code-share deals with carriers in Europe, but
its only financial investment is a 5 percent equity stake in
Swissair.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
