<SLUG> BC-SHUTTLE-MIR-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NASA PREPARES FOR SHUTTLE LAUNCH AS RUSSIANS FIX MIR'S STEERING 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MARK CARREAU 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. _ With some difficulty, the Russians
regained steering control of their drifting Mir space station
Monday, satisfying NASA that it was safe to proceed with a final
U.S. shuttle visit.
</P>
<P>
   The shuttle Discovery and a six-member crew were to blast off
from the Kennedy Space Center at 6:09 p.m., EDT, Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Shuttle program managers planned to monitor the Russian repair
effort through the night but did not slow efforts to dispatch
Discovery.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. astronaut Andy Thomas, who boarded Mir in late January,
waited eagerly for the arrival of his ride back to Earth on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   At midday Monday, Mir cosmonauts Talgat Musabayev and Nikolai
Budarin and their flight control team in suburban Moscow managed to
restart the station's steering system after two days of slow but
uncontrolled drift. The system constantly steers Mir so that its
power generating solar arrays gather the sunlight required to
generate electricity.
</P>
<P>
   NASA's experts acknowledged that the underlying cause of the
steering problem had not been pinpointed, though it seemed to
reside in the primary sensor that measures Mir's turning motions.
Those rates are then transmitted to the guidance computer so that
it can command the station's turbinelike gyrodynes to move the
outpost.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, the Russians believed the difficulty was in the
system's software, then the guidance computer itself. The computer
was replaced by the Mir crew Sunday but balked at accepting
information from the rate sensor.
</P>
<P>
   Early Monday, the station crew switched the computer to a backup
motion sensor and succeeded in folding in the station's steering
jets. The Russians planned to wean the station from the jets to the
gyrodynes Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have more than 24 hours to watch the attitude control
system. That will be adequate to have confidence in it,'' said
Frank Culbertson, who manages NASA's cooperative human spaceflight
program with the Russians. ``We would not rush into this. We will
launch when both the Mir and shuttle are ready and safe to go.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The situation is basically under control, there is no reason
to delay,'' said Boris Sotnikov, the Russian manager for the
cooperative program. ``Rest assured, if there was any risk at all,
we would definitely decide to stop the launch and wait until the
situation was stable.''
</P>
<P>
   The loss of steering control is the first for the station since
early January. In 1997, the station was rocked by a succession of
major difficulties. Those included a collision, flash fire and
breakdowns of its life support systems, as well as the faltering of
guidance systems blamed on aging computer components.
</P>
<P>
   The recent incident has been mild in comparison.
</P>
<P>
   Without steering control, Mir is technically in a tumble and in
jeopardy of losing its ability to generate electrical power.
Fortunately, the tumble rate was small, about one revolution every
60 hours. The station remained drenched in sunlight, and there was
little power loss to the Mir's life support systems.
</P>
<P>
   The ordeal, however, forced the cancellation of the brief news
conference NASA had planned with Thomas on the eve of the shuttle
launching.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Monday's developments bolstered his spirits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's hope I can find my boarding pass,'' Thomas joked as he
spoke with NASA colleagues at the Russian ground control facility.
``I hope it's around here somewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the weekend, he had expressed some anxiety over how Mir's
difficulties would influence shuttle launch plans.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas is the seventh and final U.S. astronaut assigned to live
and work on the orbital outpost.
</P>
<P>
   Discovery's crew will deliver 3,300 pounds of food, water and
other supplies to the Russians. The shuttle astronauts plan to
return to Earth with more than a ton of U.S. research equipment and
worn out Russian gear.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
