<HEADLINE>
SUSPECTED AIDE TO GOTTI TO BE INDICTED TUESDAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ja)  
 By SELWYN RAAB   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In the next phase of the government's crackdown on
the Gambino crime family's hierarchy, a suspected top aide to the
gang's imprisoned boss, John J. Gotti, will be indicted Tuesday on
federal racketeering charges, defense lawyers say.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators said John D'Amico, who has been delegated by Gotti
to help run the Gambino family while he is in prison, would be
charged on gambling and loan sharking counts. The investigators,
who spoke on the condition of anonymity, said D'Amico would be
added as a co-defendant in a case involving Gotti's son, John A.
Gotti, who was indicted in January on extensive fraud and extortion
accusations.
</P>
<P>
   An indictment and possible conviction of D'Amico, investigators
said, would further weaken the Gambino gang, which has been
displaced by the Genovese crime family as the nation's largest and
most powerful Mafia faction. Both groups use the New York City area
as their main base of operations.
</P>
<P>
   D'Amico's lawyer, James DiPietro, said in an interview Monday
that an indictment against his client might be unsealed Tuesday in
U.S. District Court in White Plains, where the case against John A.
Gotti, known as Junior, and a dozen other co-defendants is pending.
</P>
<P>
   DiPietro said that based on what he described as ``unofficial
reports,'' he believed that D'Amico's arrest was imminent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is that D'Amico is ready on a moment's notice
to surrender,'' he said. ``There is no reason to surround his house
at 6 in the morning.'' The lawyer added that he was trying to
negotiate the terms of D'Amico's surrender.
</P>
<P>
   D'Amico, 63, has unlisted telephone numbers at his home in
Hillsdale, N.J., and at an apartment on the Upper East Side in
Manhattan and could not be reached Monday for comment. D'Amico,
according to FBI agents and his lawyer, lists his occupation as a
salesman in Manhattan for a bottled water company.
</P>
<P>
   Marvin Smilon, a spokesman for the U.S. attorney's office in
Manhattan, which is handling the case, declined to comment on the
reported charges against D'Amico.
</P>
<P>
   Federal and state investigators have identified D'Amico as one
of three capos or captains in the Gambino family who were appointed
in 1992 by the elder Gotti to administer the gang and safeguard the
financial interests of his relatives while he is imprisoned. The
other committee members, investigators said, were Gotti's brother,
Peter, 58, and Nicholas Corozzo, 58, another high-ranking capo.
</P>
<P>
   But the conviction and imprisonment last year of Corozzo and the
indictment this year of Gotti's son, who is being held without
bail, catapulted D'Amico into a position of prime importance in the
Mafia family's operations, the authorities said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   J. Bruce Mouw, the former head of the FBI's Gambino squad, said
in a recent interview that D'Amico and Peter Gotti had been running
the family although the younger Gotti, 34, had the title of acting
boss bestowed on him by his father. Other federal agents and state
investigators said John J. Gotti, 57, who is serving a life
sentence without parole in the federal prison in Marion, Ill.,
would have to rely even more on his brother, Peter, to maintain
control of the family.
</P>
<P>
   D'Amico has been arrested in New York City five times since the
age of 18 on gambling charges that usually resulted in fines
without jail time.
</P>
<P>
   Before John Gotti took control of the Gambino family in 1986,
D'Amico was viewed by federal agents as a low-level Gambino
soldier. Soon after becoming the family's chief, Gotti promoted
D'Amico to head a crew, according to Mouw, and they became frequent
companions at nightspots and race tracks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
