<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRUCK-REDESIGN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUTO MAKERS PLAN SAFETY REDESIGN 
</HEADLINE>
   (ja)  
 By KEITH BRADSHER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WINDSOR, Ontario _ The mismatch in collisions between cars and
light trucks is causing as many as 2,000 extra deaths a year on
U.S. roads, but the nation's automakers have quietly notified
regulators that they will redesign their vehicles to improve
safety, the United States' top traffic safety regulator said
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The official, Dr. Ricardo Martinez, administrator of the
National Highway Traffic Safety Administration, said the growing
popularity of sport utility vehicles, minivans and pickup trucks,
all of which are classified by the government as light trucks, was
adding to the death toll. But Detroit's Big Three, and many foreign
automakers as well, have told regulators in recent months that they
plan design changes in cars and light trucks alike to address the
problem, Martinez said.
</P>
<P>
   While sport utility vehicles in particular remain a small
percentage of the vehicles on the road, sales are growing so
quickly that steps must be taken now to prevent serious safety
problems in the future, Martinez said. Although some auto
executives have publicly questioned whether a problem exists, he
said, the industry had begun working quickly to create better
designs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some are minor modifications, some are larger modifications
that will take place down the road,'' Martinez said, refusing to
provide details. He added that the design changes were aimed at
improving safety, rather than addressing shifting tastes among
vehicle buyers as some auto executives have indicated.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez also disagreed with recent assertions by some auto
industry lobbyists that government crash tests had found little
evidence of a safety problem that light trucks inflict on cars. But
he declined to elaborate, saying test data would be released on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez spoke at the opening of the International Technical
Conference on the Enhanced Safety of Vehicles, a gathering every
two years of the world's top safety regulators and researchers. The
Canadian government is acting as host for this year's conference,
in this factory town across the Detroit River from Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   Auto industry officials at the conference declined to discuss
what they would do to improve safety. But managers for General
Motors and Ford have said in recent interviews that they will
redesign the suspensions on their sport utility vehicles so that
these trucks ride closer down to the wheels, reducing the
likelihood that in collisions they will override the bumpers and
other safety systems of cars.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez offered no details on his calculation that the
car-truck mismatch was costing 2,000 lives a year. But his aides
said later that the safety agency had arrived at the number by
calculating the number of deaths that would be avoided if all light
trucks now on the road were replaced with cars.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
