<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GOLDMAN, SACHS CONSIDERS SELLING SHARES TO PUBLIC
</P>
<P>
   Jon Corzine, senior partner at Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co., told
employees that management was considering options for the firm's
future, including taking the Wall Street firm public.
</P>
<P>
   Goldman, Sachs' partners have pondered going public several
times before, but the changes now sweeping the financial-services
industry have made the current discussion more urgent.
</P>
<P>
   SLOWDOWN IN MANUFACTURING SEEN
</P>
<P>
   The National Association of Purchasing Management's index
declined to 51.4 last month from 52.9 in April as exports faltered
and cheap imports pressured factory profits. In another economic
report, construction spending rose 0.8 percent in April, to $630.1
billion.
</P>
<P>
   NASDAQ FALLS 1.8 PERCENT, BUT DOW RISES
</P>
<P>
   Intel, which fell to a 52-week low, led technology issues down.
The technology-heavy Nasdaq fell 1.8 percent, to 1,746.82.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average rose as investors sought a safe
haven from the turmoil in Asia and Russia. The Dow climbed 22.42
points, to 8,922.37. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was little
changed.
</P>
<P>
   Treasury prices rose. The yield on the benchmark 30-year
Treasury bond declined to 5.77 percent, from 5.80 percent on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   A PLAN TO ACCOUNT FOR DERIVATIVES
</P>
<P>
   The United States' accounting rule makers have approved a
proposal that will force companies to record the value of
derivatives in their financial statements.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIAN STOCK MARKET PLUMMETS
</P>
<P>
   Russia's financial crisis worsened. The Russian stock market
fell more than 10 percent; there were signs of strain among banks,
and Russia's stock futures market suspended trading.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN KEY TO ASIAN RECOVERY
</P>
<P>
   Deputy Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers said that the health
and direction of the Japanese economy was an important factor in
the Asian recovery.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVELERS CONFIRMS STAKE IN NIKKO
</P>
<P>
   As expected, Travelers Group will acquire a 25 percent stake in
Nikko Securities, Japan's third-largest securities firm, for $1.6
billion. The announcement of the deal raised questions about how
quickly the Japanese financial industry would consolidate.
</P>
<P>
   OVITZ FACES MAJOR FISCAL CHALLENGE
</P>
<P>
   Michael Ovitz, who was ousted as president of Walt Disney, faces
major challenges when he takes over Livent this week. Livent, the
producer of recent Broadway musicals like ``Ragtime'' and ``Kiss of
the Spider Woman,'' and the only publicly held company whose
primary business is live theater production, has lost $50 million
in the last 15 months.
</P>
<P>
   WIRELESS PHONE CROSSES CONTINENTS
</P>
<P>
   Audiovox and Bosch Telecom have developed a wireless phone that
can operate on different continents without modification.
</P>
<P>
   FDA APPROVES HIV URINE TEST
</P>
<P>
   The FDA approved marketing of Calypte Biomedical's urine test
for HIV. The test is the first complete urine-based diagnostic kit
for HIV that does not require confirmation by blood test.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
